3 Design Variance
The design variance of the HT mean is:
\[
\operatorname{Var}_{p}\left(\hat{\theta}^{HT}_d\right)
=
\frac{1}{N_d^2}
\sum_{i \in U_d}\sum_{j \in U_d}
\Delta_{dij}
\frac{y_{di}}{\pi_{di}}
\frac{y_{dj}}{\pi_{dj}}.
\]
An unbiased sample estimator is:
\[
\widehat{\operatorname{Var}}_{p}\left(\hat{\theta}^{HT}_d\right)
=
\frac{1}{N_d^2}
\sum_{i \in s_d}\sum_{j \in s_d}
\frac{\Delta_{dij}}{\pi_{dij}}
\frac{y_{di}}{\pi_{di}}
\frac{y_{dj}}{\pi_{dj}}.
\]
In practice, many public survey files do not provide enough information to calculate this expression directly. If design variables, replicate weights, or finite population corrections are available, use the survey producer’s recommended method or the survey package.

1 Source Files
The NSW materials used here are copied into tutorial-sae/raw so the worked example can run inside this Quarto project:

the UK Data Service respondent file, tutorial-sae/raw/nsw_2022-23_respondent_file_for_ukds.tab;
the data user guide, which explains the survey design and weight choices;
the telephone questionnaire, which explains question wording, routing, and response codes;
the variable catalogue, which gives variable labels and missing-value conventions;
Census 2021 Local Authority tables in tutorial-sae/raw/census, used for domain sizes.

The user guide says the survey is designed to provide representative information about adults aged 16+ in private households in Wales, with results available down to Local Authority level. The public respondent file contains DvLA, a derived Local Authority variable, but not a finer public geography. That makes Local Authority the finest target domain used in this tutorial.






Note



This is a substantive SAE decision. If a survey file only identifies respondents to Local Authority, then Ward, MSOA, or LSOA estimates would require extra spatial information or a defensible linkage. In this public NSW file, the tutorial stays at Local Authority.

3 Load the Respondent File
The respondent file is tab-separated. The catalogue and questionnaire use negative values such as -99, -98, -9, -8, and sometimes -7 for refused, don’t know, routed, or other non-substantive responses. We keep those visible at import and handle them explicitly when constructing indicators.

nsw_raw &lt;- read_tsv(respondent_file, show_col_types = FALSE)

missing_codes &lt;- c(-99, -98, -9, -8, -7)

is_missing_code &lt;- function(x) {
  is.na(x) | x %in% missing_codes
}

make_binary &lt;- function(x, yes_values) {
  case_when(
    is_missing_code(x) ~ NA_integer_,
    x %in% yes_values ~ 1L,
    TRUE ~ 0L
  )
}

The notebook creates la_code from DvLA. The public file does not provide DvLACd, so we reconstruct the standard Welsh Local Authority code and then apply the two code corrections used in the notebook.

nsw &lt;- nsw_raw |&gt;
  mutate(
    la_code = str_c("W0", as.integer(DvLA) + 6000000L),
    la_code = recode(
      la_code,
      "W06000007" = "W06000023", # Powys
      "W06000017" = "W06000024"  # Merthyr Tydfil
    )
  )

6 Prepare Domain Sizes
For the current SAE workflow, the domain-size table needs one row per Local Authority. The notebook uses Census 2021 tables:

TS007 for age, used to construct adults aged 16+;
TS041 for household counts.


pop_adult &lt;- read_csv(
  file.path(census_root, "census2021-ts007-ltla.csv"),
  show_col_types = FALSE
) |&gt;
  filter(str_starts(`geography code`, "W")) |&gt;
  transmute(
    la_code = `geography code`,
    pop_16plus =
      `Age: Total; measures: Value` -
      `Age: Aged 4 years and under; measures: Value` -
      `Age: Aged 5 to 9 years; measures: Value` -
      `Age: Aged 10 to 15 years; measures: Value`
  )

households &lt;- read_csv(
  file.path(census_root, "census2021-ts041-ltla.csv"),
  show_col_types = FALSE
) |&gt;
  filter(str_starts(`geography code`, "W")) |&gt;
  transmute(
    la_code = `geography code`,
    household_total =
      `Number of households: Number of households; measures: Value`
  )

domain_sizes &lt;- pop_adult |&gt;
  left_join(households, by = "la_code")

write_csv(domain_sizes, file.path(clean_dir, "pop_estimate.csv"))

This creates two denominators because the estimands use two different target populations. Household car access should use households. Adult travel indicators should use the adult population aged 16+.

9 What This Demonstrates
This worked example follows the same workflow as the preparation page:

the estimand controls the target population and interpretation;
the indicator is coded from the questionnaire and catalogue, with missing and routed values handled explicitly;
the target domain is Local Authority because that is the spatial information available in the public survey file;
the domain size comes from external Census tables and must match the estimand;
the weight must match the target population and, for this direct-estimation workflow, be on a compatible scale.

The output of this page is the set of files used in the estimation workflow: one respondent-level indicator-weight file per estimand, plus one Local Authority domain-size file.

